aky fixes and GitHub issues for real bugs.\\n     4→---\\n     5→\\n     6→# E2E Triage\\n     7→\\n     8→Triage E2E test failures with **re-run verification**. Operates in two modes (auto-detected), analyzes artifacts, and re-runs failing tests to distinguish flaky from real bugs. **Local mode** presents findings interactively and applies fixes directly in the working tree. **CI mode** creates batched PRs for flaky fixes and GitHub issues for real bugs.\\n     9→\\n    10→## Mode Detection\\n    11→\\n    12→The two modes share the same analysis and classification logic but differ in how results are presented and acted upon. Local mode is interactive (user reviews findings, chooses what to fix); CI mode is automated (PRs and issues created directly).\\n    13→\\n    14→- **CI mode**: `WORKFLOW_RUN_ID` env var is set (injected by `e2e-triage.yml`)\\n    15→- **Local mode**: No `WORKFLOW_RUN_ID` — user invokes `/e2e-triage` manually\\n    16→\\n    17→---\\n    18→\\n    19→## Local Mode\\n    20→\\n    21→### Step L1: Parse User Input\\n    22→\\n    23→The user provides one or more of:\\n    24→- **Test name(s)** — e.g., `TestInteractiveMultiStep`\\n    25→- **`--agent <agent>`** — optional, defaults to all agents that previously failed\\n    26→- **A local artifact path** — skip straight to analysis of existing artifacts\\n    27→\\n    28→**Cost warning:** Real E2E tests consume API tokens. Before running, confirm with the user unless they provided specific test names (implying intent to run).\\n    29→\\n    30→### Step L2: First Run\\n    31→\\n    32→```bash\\n    33→mise run test:e2e --agent <agent> <TestName>\\n    34→```\\n    35→\\n    36→Capture the artifact directory from the `artifacts: <path>` output line.\\n    37→\\n    38→### Step L3: Re-run on Failure\\n    39→\\n    40→If the test **passes** on first run: report as passing, done for this test.\\n    41→\\n    42→If the test **fails**: run a **second time** with the same parameters.\\n    43→\\n    44→### Step L4: Tiebreaker (if needed)\\n    45→\\n    46→If results are **split** (1 pass, 1 fail): run a **third time** as tiebreaker.\\n    47→\\n    48→### Step L5: Collect Results\\n    49→\\n    50→For each test+agent pair, record: `(test, agent, run_1_result, run_2_result, [run_3_result])`\\n    51→\\n    52→Proceed to **Shared Analysis** (Step 1 below).\\n    53→\\n    54→---\\n    55→\\n    56→## CI Mode\\n    57→\\n    58→### Step C1: Download Artifacts\\n    59→\\n    60→**If given a run ID, URL, or \\\"latest\\\":**\\n    61→```bash\\n    62→artifact_dir=$(scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh <input>)\\n    63→```\\n    64→\\n    65→**If `WORKFLOW_RUN_ID` is set (automated trigger):**\\n    66→```bash\\n    67→artifact_dir=\\\"e2e/artifacts/ci-${WORKFLOW_RUN_ID}\\\"\\n    68→```\\n    69→\\n    70→The download step in the workflow has already placed artifacts there.\\n    71→\\n    72→### Step C2: Identify Failures\\n    73→\\n    74→For each agent subdirectory in the artifact root:\\n    75→1. Read `report.nocolor.txt` — list failed tests with error messages, file:line references\\n    76→2. Skip agents with zero failures\\n    77→3. Build failure list: `[(test_name, agent, error_line, duration, file:line)]`\\n    78→\\n    79→### Step C3: Re-run Failing Tests via CI\\n    80→\\n    81→For each failing test+agent pair, **sequentially**:\\n    82→\\n    83→1. **Trigger re-run:**\\n    84→   ```bash\\n    85→   gh workflow run e2e-isolated.yml -f agent=<agent> -f test=<TestName>\\n    86→   ```\\n    87→\\n    88→2. **Wait for run to register** (~5s), then find the run ID:\\n    89→   ```bash\\n    90→   gh run list -w e2e-isolated.yml -L 1 --json databaseId -q '.[0].databaseId'\\n    91→   ```\\n    92→\\n    93→3. **Poll until complete** (check every 30s, timeout after 25 minutes):\\n    94→   ```bash\\n    95→   gh run view <run-id> --json status,conclusion\\n    96→   ```\\n    97→\\n    98→4. **Download re-run artifacts:**\\n    99→   ```bash\\n   100→   gh run download <run-id> --dir <rerun-artifact-dir>\\n   101→   ```\\n   102→\\n   103→5. **Repeat for a second re-run** (same test+agent).\\n   104→\\n   105→### Step C4: Collect Results\\n   106→\\n   107→For each test+agent pair, record: `(test, agent, original_result, rerun_1_result, rerun_2_result)`\\n   108→\\n   109→Proceed to **Shared Analysis** (Step 1 below).\\n   110→\\n   111→---\\n   112→\\n   113→## Shared Analysis & Classification\\n   114→\\n   115→### Step 1: Analyze Each Failure\\n   116→\\n   117→For each failure, follow the **Debugging Workflow** in `.claude/skills/debug-e2e/SKILL.md` (steps 2-5: console.log → test source → entire.log → deep dive). Collect:\\n   118→- What the agent actually did (from console.log)\\n   119→- What was expected (from test source)\\n   120→- CLI-level errors or anomalies (from entire.log)\\n   121→- Repo/checkpoint state (from git-log.txt, git-tree.txt, checkpoint-metadata/)\\n   122→\\n   123→### Step 2: Classify Each Failure\\n   124→\\n   125→Use **re-run results as the primary signal**, supplemented by artifact analysis.\\n   126→\\n   127→#### Re-run signals (strongest):\\n   128→\\n   129→| Original | Re-run 1 | Re-run 2 | Classification |\\n   130→|----------|----------|----------|----------------|\\n   131→| FAIL | FAIL (same error) | FAIL (same error) | **real-bug** OR **flaky (test-bug)** — see below |\\n   132→| FAIL | PASS | PASS | **flaky** |\\n   133→| FAIL | PASS | FAIL | **flaky** (non-deterministic) |\\n   134→| FAIL | FAIL | PASS | **flaky** (non-deterministic) |\\n   135→| FAIL | FAIL (different error) | FAIL (different error) | **needs deeper analysis** — examine artifacts |\\n   136→\\n   137→**Important: Consistent failures can still be `flaky` (test-bug).** When all re-runs fail, check *where* the root cause is:\\n   138→- Root cause in `cmd/entire/cli/` → **real-bug** (product code is broken)\\n   139→- Root cause in `e2e/` (test infra, test helpers, tmux setup, env propagation) → **flaky (test-bug)** — the CLI works fine, the test is broken\\n   140→\\n   141→#### Strong `real-bug` signals (root cause must be in `cmd/entire/cli/`, not `e2e/`):\\n   142→\\n   143→- `entire.log` contains `\\\"level\\\":\\\"ERROR\\\"` or panic/stack traces from CLI code\\n   144→- Checkpoint metadata structurally corrupt (malformed JSON, missing `checkpoint_id`/`strategy`)\\n   145→- Session state file missing or malformed when expected\\n   146→- Hooks did not fire at all (no `hook invoked` log entries)\\n   147→- Shadow/metadata branch has wrong tree structure\\n   148→- Same test fails across 3+ agents with same non-timeout symptom\\n   149→- Error references CLI code (panic in `cmd/entire/cli/`)\\n   150→\\n   151→**Key question:** Is the bug in `cmd/entire/cli/` (product code) or in `e2e/` (test code)? Only the former is a `real-bug`.\\n   152→\\n   153→#### Strong `flaky` signals (unless overridden by real-bug):\\n   154→\\n   155→**Agent behavior (non-deterministic):**\\n   156→- `signal: killed` (timeout)\\n   157→- `context deadline exceeded` or `WaitForCheckpoint.*exceeded deadline`\\n   158→- Agent asked for confirmation instead of acting\\n   159→- Agent created file at wrong path / wrong name\\n   160→- Agent produced no output\\n   161→- Agent committed when it shouldn't have (or vice versa)\\n   162→- Duration near timeout limit\\n   163→\\n   164→**Test-bug (consistent failure, but root cause is in `e2e/` not `cmd/entire/cli/`):**\\n   165→- Agent \\\"Not logged in\\\" / auth errors → test env setup doesn't propagate auth credentials\\n   166→- Env vars not propagated to agent session → tmux/test harness bug\\n   167→- Error references test code (`e2e/`) not CLI code (`cmd/entire/cli/`)\\n   168→- Test helper logic errors (wrong assertions, bad globs, incorrect expected values)\\n   169→- Consistent failure BUT root cause traced to `e2e/` code, not `cmd/entire/cli/`\\n   170→- Test setup/teardown issues (missing git config, temp dir cleanup, port conflicts)\\n   171→\\n   172→#### Ambiguous cases:\\n   173→\\n   174→Read `entire.log` carefully:\\n   175→- If hooks fired correctly and metadata is valid -> lean **flaky**\\n   176→- If hooks fired but produced wrong results -> lean **real-bug**\\n   177→\\n   178→### Step 3: Cross-Agent Correlation\\n   179→\\n   180→Before acting, check correlations using re-run data:\\n   181→- Same test fails for 3+ agents, all re-runs also fail -> strong **real-bug**\\n   182→- Same test fails for multiple agents, but re-runs pass -> **flaky** (shared prompt issue)\\n   183→- One agent fails consistently, others pass -> agent-specific issue (still **real-bug** if re-runs confirm)\\n   184→\\n   185→### Step 4a: Take Action — Local Mode\\n   186→\\n   187→In local mode, present findings interactively. **Do not** create branches, PRs, or GitHub issues.\\n   188→\\n   189→#### Present Findings Report\\n   190→\\n   191→For each test+agent pair, print a findings block:\\n   192→\\n   193→```\\n   194→## <TestName> (<agent>) — <classification>\\n   195→\\n   196→**Re-run results:** original=FAIL, rerun1=PASS, rerun2=PASS\\n   197→**Evidence:**\\n   198→- <1-2 sentence summary of what went wrong>\\n   199→- <key artifact evidence: entire.log excerpt, console.log excerpt, etc.>\\n   200→```\\n   201→\\n   202→#### For `flaky` failures: describe the proposed fix\\n   203→\\n   204→For agent-behavior flaky issues, fixes typically modify test prompts. For test-bug flaky issues, fixes target `e2e/` infrastructure code (harness setup, helpers, env propagation).\\n   205→\\n   206→```\\n   207→**Proposed fix:** <description>\\n   208→  - File: <path to test file or e2e infrastructure file>\\n   209→  - Change: <what will be modified — e.g., append \\\"Do not ask for confirmation\\\" to prompt, or fix env propagation in NewTmuxSession>\\n   210→```\\n   211→\\n   212→Common flaky fixes (same as CI mode):\\n   213→- Agent asked for confirmation -> append \\\"Do not ask for confirmation\\\" to 